Class RxTableWithMovableRecordControls<TableModelType extends javax.swing.table.TableModel & CollectionReorderable>

  • java.lang.Object
    • java.awt.Component
      • java.awt.Container
        • javax.swing.JComponent
          • javax.swing.JPanel
            • com.gmail.at.kevinburnseit.rxtable.RxTableWithMovableRecordControls<TableModelType>
  • Type Parameters:
    TableModelType - This is a virtual (anded) interface for TableModel and CollectionReorderable. For convenience, ArrayListWithTableModel is provided should it meet your needs; otherwise, you must parameterize any instances of this class with a class which extends both TableModel and CollectionReorderable.
    All Implemented Interfaces:
    java.awt.image.ImageObserver, java.awt.MenuContainer, java.io.Serializable, javax.accessibility.Accessible

    public class RxTableWithMovableRecordControls<TableModelType extends javax.swing.table.TableModel & CollectionReorderable>
extends javax.swing.JPanel

    A widget that provides a table within a scroll pane, along with actions to add, remove, and reorder records in the table.

    The actions are implemented both by push buttons, which are by default below the table, and by popup menu items, which can be retrieved by right-clicking on either the table or its scroll pane (if the table doesn't fully fill the scroll pane).

    Because the table supports reordering records, the records must themselves be orderable--that is to say, each record must be have a one-to-one relationship with its index in its collection. In order to facilitate record reordering, the table's model is required to also implement CollectionReorderable. As a convenience, two collection classes are provided which may well work for your needs:

    • ArrayListReorderable is just an ArrayList which implements CollectionReorderable.
    • ArrayListWithTableModel provides a TableModel on ArrayListReorderable. That abstract class meets the parameterization requirements of this widget.-

    Additionally, this widget automatically sets the selection mode to ListSelectionModel.SINGLE_SELECTION because currently the widget is not set up to perform the record manipulation functions on a selection which contains multiple records. For that reason, it is strongly recommended that you leave this setting alone.

    This class provides several constructors which are similar to those of JTable:

    • RxTableWithMovableRecordControls()
    • #RxTableWithMovableRecordControls(TableModelType)
    • #RxTableWithMovableRecordControls(TableModelType, TableColumnModel)
    • #RxTableWithMovableRecordControls(TableModelType, TableColumnModel, ListSelectionModel)

    However, due to the parameterization requirements, other JTable-like constructors, such as those that provide a table with a fixed number of rows or columns, cannot be replicated here. In any event, those constructors bypass the model-view-controller paradigm and probably shouldn't be used anyway.

    Direct manipulation of the enclosed JTable is beyond the scope of this class and should be done directly, with one exception. Changing the model associated with the table must be done using #setTableModel(TableModelType). Otherwise, the table can be manipulated by fetching the table using getTable() and operating directly on the returned object. If you need access to the table's scroll pane, such as for setting its size, call getScrollPane() and operate on it directly.

    This widget performs or facilitates six actions on the underlying data; these actions are enumerated in RxTableWithMovableRecordControls.TableActionEnum. Detailed information on these actions is provided in the javadoc for the enum constants.

    If you want to have additional listeners notified for an action, register or unregister the listeners using addActionListener(TableActionEnum, ActionListener) or removeActionListener(TableActionEnum, ActionListener).

    This widget provides default text and a default icon for each action. Due to localization concerns, you may want to change the text or icon. To do so, call setTextForAction(TableActionEnum, String) or setIconForAction(TableActionEnum, Icon).

    By default, the action buttons are located below the table. You can change this behavior by calling setButtonsLocation(String).

    Author:
    Kevin J. Burns

    • Method Detail

      • setTableModel

        public void setTableModel(TableModelType model)
        Changes the model associated with this table. This function should be used rather than calling getTable().setModel(...) because in order for the rearrangement functionality to work the model must also extend CollectionReorderable.
        Parameters:
        model - Model to assign to table. This function indirectly calls JTable::setModel(...), so if you pass null in this parameter, you can expect an IllegalArgumentException.

      • getButtonsLocation

        public java.lang.String getButtonsLocation()
        Fetches the current location of the table manipulation buttons relative to the table.
        Returns:
        Will return one of the following values:
        • BorderLayout.NORTH
        • BorderLayout.SOUTH
        • BorderLayout.EAST
        • BorderLayout.WEST

      • setButtonsLocation

        public void setButtonsLocation(java.lang.String loc)
        Sets the location of the table manipulation buttons relative to the table.
        Parameters:
        loc - the proposed location of the buttons. Must be one of the following:
        • BorderLayout.NORTH
        • BorderLayout.SOUTH
        • BorderLayout.EAST
        • BorderLayout.WEST
        If loc is null, nothing happens. Additionally, if a disallowed value is passed, nothing happens.

      • getTable

        public RxTableWithAddedRecords getTable()
        Fetches the table associated with this widget. Do not call setModel(...) on the result of this function. Use #setTableModel(TableModelType) instead, because the data reordering functionality will not work properly if the table model does not implement CollectionReorderable.
        Returns:
